<activity><title>Extraction of Roots</title>

<task><p>Solve each equation by extraction of roots. <ol>
  <li><p><m>(x+3)^2=4</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>(3x+1)^2=25</m></p></li></ol></p></task>

<task><p>Solve. Give your answers two ways: (i) exact values and (ii) approximations rounded to thousandths.<ol>
  <li><p><m>6(x-3)^2=30</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>520+60(2+x)^2=1000</m></p></li></ol></p></task>

<task><p>Solve each formula for the requested variable.<ol>
  <li><p><m>V=\frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h~~</m> for <m>r</m></p></li>
  <li><p><m>d=h-\frac{1}{2}gt^2~~</m> for <m>t</m></p></li></ol></p></task>
</activity>

<subsection><title>Check Your Understanding</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>Sketch a graph that illustrates why a quadratic equation can have two solutions.</p></li>
<li><p>In part (d) of Activity 1, what technique did you use to solve the equation?</p></li>
<li><p>Explain how you found the solution to part (c) of Activity 2, being careful to list all the steps you used.</p></li>
<li><p>Explain how to deal with the fractions in Problem (c) of Activity 3.</p></li>
</ol></p></subsection>

<subsection><title>Wrap Up</title>
<p>In this Lesson, we worked on the following skills and goals related to quadratic models:
<ul>
<li><p>Recognize a quadratic equation and its parameters</p></li>
<li><p>Graph a parabola by plotting points</p></li>
<li><p>Solve a quadratic equation by extraction of roots</p></li>
<li><p>Use formulas that involve quadratic terms</p></li>
</ul></p>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Questions for Writing or Discussion</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>Use graphs to explain why a linear equation can have only one solution, but a quadratic equation may have two solutions.</p></li>
<li><p>Explain the difference between the volume and the surface area of a cylinder. Include units in your explanation.</p></li>
<li><p>Which of these is an exact value:  <m>\sqrt{5}</m> or <m>2.236067977</m>?</p></li>
<li><p>Delbert squared <m>-6</m> by entering <m>-6^2</m> into his calculator, and got <m>-36</m>. What went wrong?</p></li>
</ol></p></commentary>

</subsection>

